# Forge agent Definition of Done

Applies across personal forge work. Repo `AGENTS.md` adds stack-specific detail; it does not replace this.

## Before claiming done

- Run the repo’s verify path (tests, lint, typecheck, dry-run as listed in `AGENTS.md`). Prefer the `verify` skill.
- If no checks exist, say so and do the lightest sanity check available (`py_compile`, build, dry-run). Do not claim “done” on vibes alone.
- **Always review the change for quality and security** before claiming done. Same bar for agent- and human-authored code.
  - Substantive code/config/infra diffs → run `review-bugbot` and `review-security` (or `/review`) on the diff; fix valid findings or explain disagreements.
  - Tiny doc/typo-only diffs → still do an explicit quality + security pass yourself (correctness, secrets, unsafe commands, broken assumptions); full subagents optional.
- End every coding turn that changed files with this block (required — a stop hook will bounce you if verify is missing):

```markdown
## Status
- Verify: <commands> → pass|fail|n/a (why)
- Review: quality+security done | deferred (why)
```

## Diffs and secrets

- Prefer small, reviewable diffs. No drive-by refactors.
- Never commit secrets, `.env`, credentials, or Terraform state.

## Review and maintenance

- PR merge-readiness → `babysit` skill.
- Concurrency / loop / worktrees / subagents → follow always-on rule `forge-orchestration` (and `forge-workflow` skill for how-to). Do not default to one long babysitting session when that rule says to escalate.

## Ask first

- Destructive git operations, force-push, or broad refactors across unrelated files.
